  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nc9-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 credibility factors assessed; all achieved levels meet or exceed required levels. Explicitly low confidence on hemolysis model form and power-law coefficient uncertainty is documented honestly throughout the package: UQ record UQ-001 reports 95% Monte Carlo prediction intervals of ±31% on NIH, sensitivity analysis SA-001 identifies power-law coefficients C and alpha as primary drivers of prediction width (Sobol indices 0.61 and 0.24 respectively), and the discretization GCI on NIH (7.2%) is elevated relative to velocity GCI (2.1%) due to impeller gap mesh sensitivity. Despite these wide bounds, all five validation operating points fall within the 95% prediction interval, the mean absolute error (18.3%) is within the accepted tolerance for MRL 5 hemolysis prediction per FDA guidance, and the NIH predictions at all conditions remain below the clinical acceptance threshold even at the 97.5th percentile of the Monte Carlo ensemble. The low confidence is a consequence of fundamental epistemic uncertainty in the power-law hemolysis model — a limitation shared across the field and acknowledged in FDA's 2022 hemolysis guidance — rather than a deficiency in the simulation execution. Acceptance is supported by: (1) complete provenance chain from raw PIV and in-vitro data through UQ ensemble to decision; (2) independent analyst review confirming setup correctness; (3) conservative threshold assessment using upper prediction bound rather than point estimate. No weakeners identified. Package accepted at Low assurance level consistent with MRL 5 Class III VAD context.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
